{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"HTML Forms Validation","slug":"html-forms-validation","subject":"HTML","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"15 minutes","prerequisites":["HTML Forms","HTML Input Types"],"learning_objectives":["Understand client-side validation","Use required, min, max, pattern attributes","Perform regex validation","Style valid/invalid states"],"theory":"# HTML Form Validation\n\nHTML5 built-in validation allows you to check user input before it is sent to the server. This provides instant feedback and reduces server load.\n\n## Validation Attributes\n\n### 1. `required`\nSpecifies that an input field must be filled out.\n```html\n<input type=\"text\" required>\n```\n\n### 2. `min` and `max`\nSpecifies the minimum and maximum values for numeric types.\n```html\n<input type=\"number\" min=\"1\" max=\"10\">\n```\n\n### 3. `minlength` and `maxlength`\nSpecifies the length limits for text strings.\n```html\n<input type=\"password\" minlength=\"8\">\n```\n\n### 4. `pattern`\nUses a **Regular Expression (Regex)** to validate complex formats.\n```html\n<input type=\"text\" pattern=\"[A-Za-z]{3}\" title=\"3 letters only\">\n```\n\n### 5. `type` checking\nInputs like `type=\"email\"` automatically validate email formats.\n\n## CSS Pseudo-classes\nYou can style inputs based on their state:\n*   `:valid`: Styles valid inputs.\n*   `:invalid`: Styles invalid inputs.\n\n```css\ninput:invalid { border: 2px solid red; }\n```","syntax":"<input required pattern=\"regex\">","examples":[{"code":"<form>\n  <label>Zip Code (5 digits):</label>\n  <input type=\"text\" pattern=\"[0-9]{5}\" title=\"Five digit zip code\" required>\n  <input type=\"submit\">\n</form>","output":"Form denies submission if not 5 digits.","explanation":"The browser checks the regex pattern [0-9]{5} automatically."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Relying ONLY on HTML validation","correction":"HTML validation can be bypassed by hackers. ALWAYS validate data on the Server Side as well.","example":"Client-side = UX. Server-side = Security."},{"mistake":"Using confusing regex","correction":"Always provide a `title` attribute to explain what the pattern requires.","example":"pattern=\"...\" title=\"Must be 3 uppercase letters\""}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"Is HTML validation secure?","difficulty":"Intermediate","answer":"No. A user can disable JavaScript or inspector tools to remove the required attributes. It is purely for User Experience (UX). Security validation happens on the server."},{"question":"What is the pattern attribute?","difficulty":"Advanced","answer":"It allows validation against a custom Regular Expression (e.g., checking for a specific ID format)."}],"practice_problems":[{"difficulty":"Intermediate","problem":"Create an input for 'Age' that is required and accepts numbers between 18 and 99.","hint":"Use type='number', min, max, required.","solution":"<input type=\"number\" min=\"18\" max=\"99\" required>"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Password Strength","description":"Signup forms use patterns to enforce 'At least one number, one uppercase' rules instantly.","code":"pattern=\"(?=.*\\d)(?=.*[a-z])(?=.*[A-Z]).{8,}\""}],"exam_notes":["required = Cannot be empty","type='email' checks @ symbol","pattern uses Regex","Always validate on server too"],"summary":"HTML Form Validation provides a way to ensure data integrity before it leaves the browser. By using simple attributes like `required` and `pattern`, you can prevent errors and guide users to correct format input instantly.","order":19},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"html-document-structure","path":"content/html/html-document-structure.json","title":"HTML Document Structure","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"html-comments","path":"content/html/html-comments.json","title":"HTML Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"html-editors","path":"con